\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 The Effect of Intermittent Fasting on Glycemic Control in Adults with Type 2 Diabetes: A Randomized Controlled Trial\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Intermittent fasting (IF) has gained attention as a potential strategy for improving metabolic health. Its effects on glycemic control in adults with type 2 diabetes (T2D) remain unclear.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To evaluate the impact of a 12-week intermittent fasting regimen on fasting blood glucose, HbA1c, body weight, and lipid profile in adults with T2D.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  In this randomized controlled trial, 120 adults with T2D were assigned to either an intermittent fasting group (IF, n = 60) or a control group receiving standard dietary advice (CON, n = 60). IF participants adhered to a 16:8 fasting protocol (16 hours fasting, 8 hours eating) daily for 12 weeks. Fasting blood glucose, HbA1c, body mass index (BMI), waist circumference, and lipid profile were measured at baseline and at the end of the study. Data were analyzed using repeated-measures ANOVA and intention-to-treat principles.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  After 12 weeks, the IF group showed a significant reduction in fasting blood glucose (mean change: \uc0\u8722 18.6 mg/dL, p < 0.001) and HbA1c (mean change: \u8722 0.8%, p < 0.001) compared to the control group (\u8722 4.2 mg/dL and \u8722 0.2%, respectively). The IF group also experienced a mean weight loss of 4.3 kg and reduction in waist circumference of 3.5 cm, both significantly greater than the control group (p < 0.01). Improvements in total cholesterol and triglycerides were observed in the IF group, although HDL and LDL changes were not statistically significant.\

\f1\b Conclusions:
\f0\b0  A 12-week intermittent fasting regimen improves glycemic control and induces modest weight loss in adults with T2D. IF may be a practical adjunct to standard dietary management for T2D, but long-term effects and safety require further study.\
