\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Type 2 diabetes (T2D) is a chronic metabolic disorder characterized by insulin resistance and impaired glucose regulation. Its prevalence has increased globally, presenting significant public health challenges due to associated complications such as cardiovascular disease, neuropathy, nephropathy, and retinopathy. Lifestyle interventions, particularly diet and physical activity, remain cornerstone strategies for glycemic management.\
Intermittent fasting (IF) has emerged as a promising dietary approach, involving alternating periods of energy restriction and ad libitum feeding. Common patterns include alternate-day fasting, 5:2 fasting, and time-restricted feeding, where individuals fast for a set number of hours each day. Evidence from animal studies and small human trials suggests that IF can improve insulin sensitivity, reduce body weight, and favorably modify lipid profiles. However, research specifically targeting adults with T2D is limited, and existing studies show heterogeneous results.\
This study aims to investigate the effects of a 12-week time-restricted intermittent fasting regimen on glycemic control, body composition, and lipid profile in adults with T2D. We hypothesized that IF would significantly improve fasting blood glucose and HbA1c levels compared to standard dietary advice.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
