\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Methods\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Study Design and Participants\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This single-center, randomized controlled trial was conducted over 12 weeks. Participants were recruited from a community diabetes clinic and screened for eligibility. Inclusion criteria were: age 30\'9665 years, diagnosed with T2D for at least 1 year, BMI 25\'9640 kg/m\'b2, and stable antidiabetic medication use for \uc0\u8805 3 months. Exclusion criteria included pregnancy, type 1 diabetes, history of eating disorders, chronic kidney or liver disease, or recent cardiovascular events.\
Eligible participants provided written informed consent and were randomized in a 1:1 ratio to the IF or control group using a computer-generated sequence. Randomization was stratified by sex and baseline HbA1c to ensure balance.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Intervention\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Participants in the IF group followed a 16:8 time-restricted fasting protocol: daily fasting for 16 consecutive hours and consuming all meals within an 8-hour window, typically between 10:00 AM and 6:00 PM. Water, black coffee, and unsweetened tea were allowed during fasting periods. Participants received dietary counseling to maintain habitual caloric intake and avoid compensatory overeating.\
The control group received standard dietary advice according to national guidelines for T2D management, emphasizing balanced macronutrient intake, portion control, and regular meal timing.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Outcome Measures\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Primary outcomes were changes in fasting blood glucose and HbA1c from baseline to 12 weeks. Secondary outcomes included body weight, BMI, waist circumference, and lipid profile (total cholesterol, HDL, LDL, triglycerides).\
Measurements were performed at baseline and at 12 weeks by trained personnel blinded to group allocation. Fasting blood samples were analyzed using standardized enzymatic methods. Weight and height were measured using calibrated scales and stadiometers, and BMI was calculated as weight in kilograms divided by height in meters squared. Waist circumference was measured at the midpoint between the lowest rib and iliac crest.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Adherence and Safety\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Participants in the IF group kept daily fasting logs, and adherence was defined as \uc0\u8805 80% of fasting days completed. Adverse events, including hypoglycemia, dizziness, or gastrointestinal discomfort, were recorded throughout the study.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Statistical Analysis\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Sample size calculations estimated that 50 participants per group would provide 80% power to detect a 0.5% difference in HbA1c between groups, assuming a standard deviation of 0.8%, at a two-sided \uc0\u945  of 0.05. To account for potential dropouts, 60 participants per group were recruited.\
Data were analyzed using intention-to-treat principles. Continuous variables were expressed as mean \'b1 standard deviation. Repeated-measures ANOVA was used to assess changes over time and between-group differences. Post hoc analyses were conducted using Bonferroni correction. Categorical variables were compared using chi-square tests. Statistical significance was set at p < 0.05.\
