\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Results\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Participant Flow and Baseline Characteristics\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Of 160 individuals screened, 120 met inclusion criteria and were randomized (IF: n = 60; CON: n = 60). Four participants in the IF group and five in the control group discontinued before study completion due to personal reasons or loss to follow-up. The final analysis included all participants under intention-to-treat principles.\
Baseline characteristics were comparable between groups (Table 1). Mean age was 52.3 \'b1 8.1 years, 55% were female, mean BMI was 32.1 \'b1 3.8 kg/m\'b2, mean fasting blood glucose was 154.2 \'b1 22.7 mg/dL, and mean HbA1c was 7.9 \'b1 0.8%.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Primary Outcomes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 After 12 weeks, the IF group experienced a significant reduction in fasting blood glucose (\uc0\u8722 18.6 \'b1 12.4 mg/dL) compared to the control group (\u8722 4.2 \'b1 10.7 mg/dL, p < 0.001). HbA1c decreased by 0.8 \'b1 0.5% in the IF group versus 0.2 \'b1 0.4% in controls (p < 0.001) (Figure 1).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Secondary Outcomes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The IF group lost an average of 4.3 \'b1 2.1 kg compared to 0.9 \'b1 1.8 kg in the control group (p < 0.01). Waist circumference decreased by 3.5 \'b1 1.7 cm in IF participants versus 0.8 \'b1 1.5 cm in controls (p < 0.01). BMI reduction was more pronounced in the IF group (\uc0\u8722 1.5 \'b1 0.7 kg/m\'b2) compared to controls (\u8722 0.3 \'b1 0.6 kg/m\'b2, p < 0.01).\
Total cholesterol decreased modestly in the IF group (\uc0\u8722 12.4 \'b1 15.6 mg/dL) versus controls (\u8722 3.1 \'b1 14.2 mg/dL, p = 0.02). Triglycerides fell by 18.7 \'b1 22.1 mg/dL in IF participants compared to 5.2 \'b1 19.3 mg/dL in controls (p = 0.01). Changes in HDL and LDL cholesterol were not statistically significant between groups.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Adherence and Safety\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Adherence to the IF protocol was high, with 85% of participants completing \uc0\u8805 80% of fasting days. Mild hypoglycemia was reported in 6 participants in the IF group, all managed with dietary adjustments. No serious adverse events occurred.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
