\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This randomized controlled trial demonstrates that a 12-week intermittent fasting regimen significantly improves glycemic control and induces modest weight loss in adults with T2D. The observed reduction in fasting blood glucose (\uc0\u8722 18.6 mg/dL) and HbA1c (\u8722 0.8%) is clinically meaningful, comparable to the effect of adding a single oral antidiabetic agent.\
The improvements in body weight and waist circumference suggest that time-restricted fasting may reduce central adiposity, a key contributor to insulin resistance. Modest reductions in total cholesterol and triglycerides further indicate potential cardiovascular benefits. The lack of significant changes in HDL and LDL cholesterol may reflect the short duration of the intervention.\
High adherence and minimal adverse events suggest that time-restricted fasting is a feasible and safe dietary strategy for adults with T2D. However, careful monitoring is required, particularly for individuals on insulin or sulfonylureas, due to risk of hypoglycemia.\
Mechanistically, IF may improve glycemic control by enhancing insulin sensitivity, promoting beta-cell function, and modulating circadian rhythms related to metabolism. Fasting periods may also reduce postprandial glucose excursions and lower systemic inflammation.\
Limitations of this study include its relatively short duration, single-center design, and reliance on self-reported adherence. Long-term effects on glycemic control, cardiovascular outcomes, and quality of life remain to be established. Future studies should explore different fasting protocols, effects in patients on various antidiabetic medications, and integration with lifestyle interventions such as exercise.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
